%N A342597 a(n) is the number of nodes of degree 3 or 4 that are at distance n from the origin in the graph of the Hofstetter-4fold tiling; a(0) = 1.
%C A342597 We build the Hofstetter-4fold tiling as follows:
%C A342597 - H_0 corresponds to a 2 X 2 square:
%C A342597       +---+---+
%C A342597       |       |
%C A342597       +       +
%C A342597       |       |
%C A342597       +---+---+
%C A342597      O
%C A342597 - for any k >= 0, H_{k+1} is obtained by arranging 4 copies of H_k, rotated by 0, 90, 180, 270 degrees clockwise respectively, as follows:
%C A342597                             +.......+
%C A342597                             .     90.
%C A342597       +.......+         +.......+   ....+
%C A342597       .       .         .0      .   .   .
%C A342597       .       .   -->   .       .....   .
%C A342597       .       .         .       .    180.
%C A342597       +.......+         +.......+.......+
%C A342597      O                 O    .270    .
%C A342597                             +.......+
%C A342597 - note that:
%C A342597    - the copy rotated by 0 degrees hides some squares on the copies rotated by 90 and 270 degrees,
%C A342597    - the copy rotated by 90 degrees hides some squares on the copy rotated by 180 degrees,
%C A342597    - the copy rotated by 180 degrees hides some squares on the copy rotated by 270 degrees,
%C A342597 - the Hofstetter-4fold tiling corresponds to the limit of H_k as k tends to infinity.
